1
00:00:00,537 --> 00:00:29,007
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhassa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhassa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhassa

2
00:00:30,321 --> 00:00:34,688
homage to the blessed, noble, and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:39,814 --> 00:00:56,497
So, I thought I'd try and make a fairly sort of false statement about this wheel of dependent origination, just so that I've got a cassette to show people when they get confused about it.

4
00:00:58,957 --> 00:01:00,901
Saves me saying the same thing over and over again.

5
00:01:06,168 --> 00:01:09,412
First of all, just to put it into the perspective of the Buddha's life.

6
00:01:09,793 --> 00:01:17,963
Remember that he left home and we can presume it wasn't for frivolous reasons.

7
00:01:18,465 --> 00:01:20,147
He wasn't doing a hippie trip or something.

8
00:01:22,450 --> 00:01:27,817
He was motivated by what we would call these days an existential angst.

9
00:01:29,840 --> 00:01:38,013
It's put mythologically as him coming across these devaduttas, these messengers from the gods, as it's put.

10
00:01:38,853 --> 00:01:43,040
A sick person, an elderly person, and a corpse.

11
00:01:45,444 --> 00:01:55,881
And what it signifies is that in his middle or early twenties, he woke up to the fact that life comes to an end, there's old sickness, old age, and death.

12
00:01:57,362 --> 00:01:58,043
this through him.

13
00:01:58,745 --> 00:02:14,526
So eventually when he leaves, and he goes and practices with various teachers, and then finally, as it were, goes on his own to achieve the enlightenment, he can reduce the whole of his teaching to suffering and the end of suffering.

14
00:02:17,610 --> 00:02:18,752
That's what he says he teaches.

15
00:02:19,413 --> 00:02:23,318
He reduces it to those three words, suffering and the end of suffering.

16
00:02:23,338 --> 00:02:24,501
It's three words in the Pali.

17
00:02:26,810 --> 00:02:29,836
And what he discovers of course is the way out.

18
00:02:31,259 --> 00:02:35,008
And luckily for us he has this ability to get it across.

19
00:02:36,170 --> 00:02:40,980
And what he gives us is a psychological paradigm.

20
00:02:42,084 --> 00:02:46,252
And I think it's very important for meditators to know this.

21
00:02:46,687 --> 00:02:56,935
Because if we don't, we come to the meditation with our own psychological paradigm, which is got from our own tradition of psychology, psychotherapy.

22
00:02:57,201 --> 00:02:58,604
Not that that's all wrong.

23
00:02:59,245 --> 00:03:00,045
It isn't at all.

24
00:03:00,606 --> 00:03:06,415
But when the Buddha's talking about psychology, he's talking about suffering and the end of suffering.

25
00:03:06,436 --> 00:03:07,277
It's specific.

26
00:03:09,221 --> 00:03:11,884
It's nothing to do with how we learn, how we develop.

27
00:03:11,925 --> 00:03:13,687
It's not developmental psychology.

28
00:03:14,549 --> 00:03:17,212
It's nothing to do with psychotherapy as such.

29
00:03:18,033 --> 00:03:23,782
It's to do with finding out how suffering arises and how it passes away.

30
00:03:24,775 --> 00:03:36,271
So if we have a clear idea of the paticca-sambhupada, the we the dependent origination, then that intelligence which is going to liberate us can see more clearly.

31
00:03:38,616 --> 00:03:44,965
This is the paradox that that intelligence which liberates us needs to be instructed on how to do it.

32
00:03:44,985 --> 00:03:47,508
It doesn't come naturally it seems.

33
00:03:51,961 --> 00:04:13,352
Now, just to put what I say in perspective, his regular companion, Ananda, who was with him for 20 odd years eventually, was obviously present for all his talks that he gave, or at least most of them, and he would obviously take the opportunity to discuss this with the Buddha when he's with him.

34
00:04:13,491 --> 00:04:18,017
I mean, he's there in the room, he's attending to the man.

35
00:04:18,038 --> 00:04:21,343
So he comes one day to this conclusion, and he says to the Buddha,

36
00:04:22,083 --> 00:04:24,805
I think I've understood this business now.

37
00:04:24,826 --> 00:04:28,449
I think I understand this wheel of dependence origination that you're teaching.

38
00:04:28,470 --> 00:04:30,632
And the Buddha says, oh no, don't say that, Ananda.

39
00:04:32,634 --> 00:04:33,536
This stuff is deep.

40
00:04:34,036 --> 00:04:36,158
This stuff is profound.

41
00:04:36,178 --> 00:04:36,800
It's subtle.

42
00:04:37,821 --> 00:04:46,250
So whatever I say must be taken in the context of that announcement of the Buddha towards Ananda.

43
00:04:49,504 --> 00:04:55,233
The first thing to understand about the Buddha's teaching is that he's not into metaphysics.

44
00:04:56,877 --> 00:05:00,742
He's not into where does the universe begin and where does it end.

45
00:05:00,903 --> 00:05:02,605
Is it eternal or not eternal?

46
00:05:02,625 --> 00:05:04,569
Is the soul lasting or not lasting?

47
00:05:04,670 --> 00:05:08,795
Is there a God or is there not a God?

48
00:05:09,336 --> 00:05:12,221
So he's not talking about origins in that sense.

49
00:05:13,483 --> 00:05:29,766
So when he points to the first link of the wheel of dependent origination, when he's pointing to the base of it, when he talks about ignorance, not knowing, he's not talking about some distant time where consciousness arose out of some primordial mass into this state of not knowing.

50
00:05:30,187 --> 00:05:36,716
He's simply saying that at this present moment, right now, consciousness is in a state of don't know.

51
00:05:38,699 --> 00:05:39,660
It doesn't know.

52
00:05:41,259 --> 00:05:43,543
That not knowing is not culpable.

53
00:05:44,103 --> 00:05:47,166
It's not as though we deserve to be not knowing.

54
00:05:47,187 --> 00:05:49,629
It's not as though we should feel guilty because we don't know.

55
00:05:50,151 --> 00:05:51,512
It's simply a state of not knowing.

56
00:05:55,117 --> 00:05:58,922
Just as when a car breaks down, we don't know.

57
00:06:00,242 --> 00:06:03,387
If you're not mechanically minded and you open the bonnet, you still don't know.

58
00:06:04,447 --> 00:06:05,548
Just don't know.

59
00:06:05,588 --> 00:06:11,115
You don't say to yourself, well, some people do, of course, I'm a fool, I should know about this, etc., etc.

60
00:06:11,136 --> 00:06:12,317
You just don't know.

61
00:06:12,358 --> 00:06:17,824
And, of course, it's a position that we as human beings find very difficult.

62
00:06:17,845 --> 00:06:18,706
We do want to know.

63
00:06:19,548 --> 00:06:21,370
We feel secure when we know.

64
00:06:21,389 --> 00:06:25,254
So you wake up and you've got a pain at the end of your nose and you're sure it's cancer.

65
00:06:26,997 --> 00:06:28,639
And you go to the doctor because you want to know.

66
00:06:28,740 --> 00:06:29,420
So what is it?

67
00:06:29,440 --> 00:06:30,201
It's just a pimple.

68
00:06:30,362 --> 00:06:30,942
He says, oh...

69
00:06:31,884 --> 00:06:34,608
Fantastic relief.

70
00:06:34,629 --> 00:06:40,197
If you said it's the most dangerous cancer, it'll blow your brains apart in two weeks and of course you'll fall apart.

71
00:06:41,240 --> 00:06:41,980
But at least we know.

72
00:06:42,021 --> 00:06:48,391
It's better for us to know we're going to be blown apart than not to know.

73
00:06:48,490 --> 00:06:50,074
It's an easier state to be in.

74
00:06:50,093 --> 00:06:51,255
We can handle that.

75
00:06:51,276 --> 00:06:51,916
We know that.

76
00:06:53,399 --> 00:06:56,884
But not to know is very difficult.

77
00:06:56,904 --> 00:06:57,605
So...

78
00:06:58,295 --> 00:07:09,005
Bringing ourselves, as it were, into this lifetime, not worrying about past lives and future lives and getting into what might seem to others to be metaphysics.

79
00:07:10,487 --> 00:07:11,649
What does the fetus know?

80
00:07:11,689 --> 00:07:13,932
What does it wake up to?

81
00:07:14,752 --> 00:07:22,581
As its sensual basis begins to develop, it begins to hear heartbeats of the mother, begins to feel the place it's in.

82
00:07:23,894 --> 00:07:32,430
And there's no doubt a time when it's absolutely gloriously in this lovely bath of warmth, being fed, growing, etc.

83
00:07:33,091 --> 00:07:36,218
And then, slowly, it becomes uncomfortable.

84
00:07:36,879 --> 00:07:42,470
Then the dreadful passage, a smack on the arse, and they're there.

85
00:07:42,490 --> 00:07:45,235
The eyes open, and suddenly, we're here.

86
00:07:46,158 --> 00:07:46,358
See?

87
00:07:47,062 --> 00:07:49,449
From a state of not knowing, we're suddenly somewhere.

88
00:07:49,629 --> 00:07:56,548
From a state of some sort of cloudy feelings, which are nice, we go through this terrible pain.

89
00:07:57,812 --> 00:07:58,634
And suddenly we're here.

90
00:07:59,055 --> 00:08:00,499
And we've got no language.

91
00:08:01,846 --> 00:08:03,086
We can't reflect on it.

92
00:08:03,767 --> 00:08:04,408
We just hear.

93
00:08:04,908 --> 00:08:05,670
Very present.

94
00:08:06,350 --> 00:08:09,995
But we're present in a total state of ignorance as to what's happening to us.

95
00:08:10,795 --> 00:08:18,343
So it's no wonder that very slowly we just come to see or we come to accept or we come to understand that this is what we are.

96
00:08:19,646 --> 00:08:20,365
I am my body.

97
00:08:21,206 --> 00:08:22,649
I am my eyes and my ears.

98
00:08:23,250 --> 00:08:24,591
I am my feelings and my thoughts.

99
00:08:25,132 --> 00:08:29,997
It's got to be a natural mistake because that's all consciousness knows.

100
00:08:31,495 --> 00:08:36,113
But it's a mistake.

101
00:08:36,133 --> 00:08:40,149
And because of that essential mistake, a load of suffering comes our way.

102
00:08:40,671 --> 00:08:42,619
In fact, all our suffering comes our way.

103
00:08:42,817 --> 00:08:51,669
And that mistake, of course, is the belief, is the conception, is the understanding that we are what we appear to be.

104
00:08:52,650 --> 00:08:53,312
Human beings.

105
00:08:54,352 --> 00:08:55,894
Psychophysical organisms.

106
00:08:56,596 --> 00:08:58,057
Rather like that phrase.

107
00:08:58,077 --> 00:09:00,400
A psychophysical organism.

108
00:09:00,421 --> 00:09:06,469
A breathing, feeling, sensing, emoting, thinking, psychophysical organism.

109
00:09:07,429 --> 00:09:08,792
And so that's what we think we are.

110
00:09:11,437 --> 00:09:15,043
So that's our first disposition, sankara.

111
00:09:15,063 --> 00:09:26,202
So from avijja, avijja, vijja means knowing, avijja means not knowing, we produce our first sankara, our first disposition, which is me, self.

112
00:09:29,408 --> 00:09:34,797
Embodied, embodied, an incarnate entity.

113
00:09:37,813 --> 00:09:43,700
So with that fundamental disposition we find ourselves in the next link, the body and the mind.

114
00:09:44,400 --> 00:09:49,986
Now, in Buddhist understanding, these are two different forms of energy.

115
00:09:50,947 --> 00:10:02,639
Both suffering from transience, both not-self, and both, if we attach to them wrongly, will create suffering, will create dissatisfaction, won't bring permanent happiness.

116
00:10:03,869 --> 00:10:11,557
But the body and mind in the Buddha's understanding are two different things, though intimately entwined as milk in water.

117
00:10:11,918 --> 00:10:21,748
But through good meditation, even in this lifetime, they can be separated as a sword can be taken from its scabbard.

118
00:10:21,768 --> 00:10:24,650
It's one of the powers that we can get if we want it.

119
00:10:25,672 --> 00:10:30,716
And then you don't have to pay anything at all to go to Mallorca and all these beautiful places.

120
00:10:31,177 --> 00:10:32,239
You just wander off.

121
00:10:34,462 --> 00:10:48,597
So, having entered into this conglomerate of the body and mind, it obviously has ways of communicating to the world and for the world to communicate to it, and that's your five senses, six senses.

122
00:10:48,618 --> 00:11:03,373
The five ordinary senses that we know, and the sixth is that part of us, the brain, and the mind which is in the brain, which is there to receive and to process stimulus, right?

123
00:11:03,707 --> 00:11:07,774
This is known in, this has got a special word for it, impali, mano.

124
00:11:11,741 --> 00:11:18,894
Now having established these qualities, having established a fundamental disposition, all these things are arising at once.

125
00:11:20,037 --> 00:11:21,700
We make contact with the world.

126
00:11:23,485 --> 00:11:26,309
So contact comes to us also from the world.

127
00:11:26,330 --> 00:11:28,133
So we hear a sound.

128
00:11:28,634 --> 00:11:32,440
The sound, as we know, is just pressure on the eardrum.

129
00:11:32,460 --> 00:11:33,562
It comes into the brain.

130
00:11:34,202 --> 00:11:38,350
And that first contact is known as pasa, is contact.

131
00:11:38,750 --> 00:11:41,595
At that point of contact, there is only...

132
00:11:42,436 --> 00:11:53,229
what is stimulating the base, the sensual base, here the eardrum, the eardrum itself, the sensual base, and this consciousness.

133
00:11:54,192 --> 00:11:55,315
Nothing else is there.

134
00:11:57,168 --> 00:12:26,095
so at primary level there is just that percept of that fundamental stimulus which is coming in at the eardrum it just is a pounding it's just the earth element it has no sound about it at all once that is there it is as it were brought into the mind which is the sense base and there it's processed and we begin to hear something

135
00:12:27,491 --> 00:12:29,817
And that's really all part of this contact.

136
00:12:30,217 --> 00:12:35,249
But when that happens, there arises in us a response.

137
00:12:36,611 --> 00:12:43,628
And the response is to perceive it, to experience it as either pleasurable or non-pleasurable.

138
00:12:44,873 --> 00:12:49,278
This is when we move on to the next stage, which is vedana, feeling.

139
00:12:49,298 --> 00:13:01,413
So from contact, which is felt as a neutral experience, we move into experiencing it as something which is pleasant and unpleasant.

140
00:13:01,433 --> 00:13:08,503
Now, this consciousness which has come into life is experiencing things as pleasant and unpleasant.

141
00:13:08,523 --> 00:13:11,927
Is it no wonder that it just wants to center on what is pleasant?

142
00:13:13,932 --> 00:13:16,716
And when it centers on what is pleasant, it finds happiness.

143
00:13:18,240 --> 00:13:25,331
So there you have your next link, tanha, which is translated, unfortunately, as craving.

144
00:13:25,633 --> 00:13:30,701
But tanha means this reaction, this reaction of wanting, not wanting.

145
00:13:32,465 --> 00:13:37,594
So from the stimulus, from the actual given percept of pasa, contact,

146
00:13:37,725 --> 00:13:45,523
we have a judgmental mind coming in at a feeling level, a feeling level saying likable, unlikable.

147
00:13:46,765 --> 00:13:50,214
There's an immediate reaction by that consciousness of saying this is it.

148
00:13:50,774 --> 00:13:52,818
If it's likable, there's wantable.

149
00:13:53,822 --> 00:13:57,168
If it's unlikable, it is definitely not wantable.

150
00:13:57,908 --> 00:14:08,214
There's a whole area in between of neutral feelings but if in your meditation you really go into the neutral feeling you'll see that there's always a shade of liking and not liking.

151
00:14:10,659 --> 00:14:15,511
These feelings are divided by the Buddha at its simplest into five.

152
00:14:15,796 --> 00:14:23,777
The physical pleasant and unpleasant feelings, such as when you're sitting there, you get pain in the knees, that's a physical unpleasant feeling.

153
00:14:24,317 --> 00:14:28,489
If you're sitting there and you're feeling very comfortable in the body, that's a pleasant physical feeling.

154
00:14:29,397 --> 00:14:33,921
There's pleasant and unpleasant mental feelings, which is basically our emotional life.

155
00:14:34,522 --> 00:14:41,629
So if you're sitting here and you feel joyful, then you're experiencing pleasant vedana, pleasant feelings.

156
00:14:41,808 --> 00:14:45,972
If you're depressed or angry or whatever, then you're feeling unpleasant stuff.

157
00:14:45,993 --> 00:14:51,938
And there's that whole business of the neutral feelings, for instance, around the breath, which are very neutral.

158
00:14:54,562 --> 00:14:56,703
So, having established that

159
00:14:57,427 --> 00:15:02,999
that vedana, that feeling base, we have this reaction of wanting and not wanting.

160
00:15:05,625 --> 00:15:13,221
When that wanting and not wanting comes up, only then, only then does the I appear.

161
00:15:16,086 --> 00:15:18,051
I want, I don't want.

162
00:15:19,297 --> 00:15:27,928
The I, the idea of a self, of me wanting something, in terms of the psychological process, comes in quite late at the end.

163
00:15:29,812 --> 00:15:38,965
That means that at that point, this consciousness has identified, has become what it is now wanting.

164
00:15:41,587 --> 00:15:45,573
So up until that point, that identity isn't there.

165
00:15:47,831 --> 00:15:48,533
We know that.

166
00:15:48,993 --> 00:15:51,176
You know that in your meditation.

167
00:15:51,196 --> 00:16:11,636
When you've sat there in your meditation and, shall we say, a depression or an angry feeling has arisen or something, or a joyful or wonderful feeling, see, and you are observing it as an object, then that I, meaning I am depressed, I am joyful, can't arise.

168
00:16:14,080 --> 00:16:16,201
It only arises when you become it.

169
00:16:16,586 --> 00:16:23,974
It only arises, for instance, when the sun comes out and you throw yourself on the lawn and suddenly you become sunshine.

170
00:16:24,355 --> 00:16:25,355
You're there with the sun.

171
00:16:27,076 --> 00:16:31,861
From a point of view of indulgence, I am this pleasant feeling.

172
00:16:33,383 --> 00:16:36,947
Because we're not enlightened, we're constantly moving in and out of that.

173
00:16:37,006 --> 00:16:42,072
Because we're meditators, we can find that position of not being that position.

174
00:16:42,878 --> 00:16:53,714
And when we fall out of that grace, we fall into the self, and we establish this relationship in the world, whereby we're seeking happiness there.

175
00:16:53,734 --> 00:16:55,075
That's what we're doing all the time.

176
00:16:55,135 --> 00:17:01,764
We're trying to seek comfort, we're trying to seek security, we're trying to seek happiness in the sensual world.

177
00:17:03,549 --> 00:17:05,375
So there's your upadana.

178
00:17:06,317 --> 00:17:16,664
When the Buddha describes the five khandhas, the five heaps that some of you will know, which is another division of the human experience.

179
00:17:17,741 --> 00:17:35,684
meaning the body, all our perceptions, all our feelings, all our emotional and mental productions, and our discriminative consciousness, he calls them the upadana khanda, he calls them the grasping khanda.

180
00:17:36,665 --> 00:17:43,934
In other words, this is only a problem when we say this is what I am, when we identify with it.

181
00:17:46,025 --> 00:17:53,435
so there's your Upadana you see now at this point not only

182
00:17:54,682 --> 00:17:58,587
At that point, the I has come in to identify.

183
00:17:58,607 --> 00:18:00,951
The next point is Bhāva.

184
00:18:01,892 --> 00:18:03,334
Bhāva means becoming.

185
00:18:04,155 --> 00:18:09,682
So now, the wanting, I want, now becomes get it.

186
00:18:10,423 --> 00:18:14,971
There's an impulsion of will into that want, and it becomes an action.

187
00:18:15,151 --> 00:18:18,836
An action of thought, an action of speech, or an action of the body.

188
00:18:19,657 --> 00:18:22,080
At which point, karma is created.

189
00:18:22,260 --> 00:18:23,423
That's an action.

190
00:18:23,403 --> 00:18:25,006
That's becoming.

191
00:18:26,449 --> 00:18:36,847
So from liking not liking, wanting not wanting, I want I don't want, I do I don't do.

192
00:18:36,867 --> 00:18:39,772
Remember that even not doing something is also an action.

193
00:18:43,278 --> 00:18:45,343
It's a decision not to do something.

194
00:18:46,740 --> 00:19:01,594
So now we've taken a whole series of progressive acts which has produced a bhava, it's produced a becoming, it's produced an act of kamma, which basically is just an action.

195
00:19:02,738 --> 00:19:14,317
Now, the importance of an action is, of course, is that because the mind is something we can condition, as soon as we put an action into the mind, an empowerment, we have conditioned it.

196
00:19:15,117 --> 00:19:19,865
The more actions we put of a similar nature, it becomes a habit.

197
00:19:19,885 --> 00:19:25,454
The more habits we engender is the definition of our personality.

198
00:19:27,140 --> 00:19:33,490
And once we have that personality, which is no more than a compendium of habits, our destiny is assured.

199
00:19:37,577 --> 00:19:45,991
So, having made this Baba, this act, we now go into the process of being born, decay and death.

200
00:19:47,221 --> 00:19:57,595
Again, keeping the weed of dependent origination right into the present moment, that simply means that the action is begun, the action is gone through, and the action is completed.

201
00:19:57,894 --> 00:19:59,217
And that's the end of the process.

202
00:20:01,861 --> 00:20:04,463
In terms of the mind, there's been a conditioning.

203
00:20:04,483 --> 00:20:07,288
There's been a conditioning set into the mind.

204
00:20:10,356 --> 00:20:17,207
So, a child, for instance, hears, just hears the little dingy bell of the ice cream man.

205
00:20:18,628 --> 00:20:21,393
Now what comes to the ear is just this little knocking.

206
00:20:22,134 --> 00:20:35,452
It's taken in, you see, and suddenly there's a perception of bell, there's a perception of the understanding of the bell, there's a perception of ice cream, there's a memory of ice cream, and joy arises.

207
00:20:35,887 --> 00:20:36,188
See?

208
00:20:36,749 --> 00:20:37,849
The joy arises.

209
00:20:38,289 --> 00:20:39,510
So this is Vedana.

210
00:20:39,652 --> 00:20:42,354
We've had the contact, this is Vedana.

211
00:20:42,374 --> 00:20:48,819
As soon as the joy arises, wanting arises, I want, jumping up and down, I want an ice cream.

212
00:20:49,760 --> 00:20:49,881
See?

213
00:20:50,541 --> 00:21:04,815
And nothing will satisfy that child now, unless he gets that ice cream, goes through the motions of eating it, swallowing it, and completing it, and feeling for a moment that lovely satisfaction, which only ice cream can give us.

214
00:21:07,006 --> 00:21:10,670
But, foolishly, he has now established a habit.

215
00:21:11,270 --> 00:21:15,195
A habit of seeking happiness in ice cream.

216
00:21:15,215 --> 00:21:21,743
Hence, whenever that ice cream van comes, out he'll go demanding his ice cream.

217
00:21:22,484 --> 00:21:28,932
Later on, of course, ice cream becomes beef stroganoff.

218
00:21:28,952 --> 00:21:30,394
Spaghetti a la Bolognese.

219
00:21:33,117 --> 00:21:34,278
Beautiful wines.

220
00:21:39,388 --> 00:21:47,980
And of course, the more we indulge in food, the more we must seek our happiness there.

221
00:21:50,001 --> 00:22:00,434
And if one day there's no food in the larder, there's no tea in the morning, there's no toast, misery, frustration, horror.

222
00:22:01,900 --> 00:22:03,262
That's the other side of the wheel.

223
00:22:03,363 --> 00:22:05,226
That's another conditioning coming up, you see.

224
00:22:05,707 --> 00:22:10,696
But anyway, that in summary is how the wheel works.

225
00:22:12,078 --> 00:22:15,526
And it works in terms of this process, you see.

226
00:22:16,106 --> 00:22:17,249
Parts of it are given.

227
00:22:17,589 --> 00:22:21,596
A state of ignorance is with us all the time until we're fully enlightened.

228
00:22:22,201 --> 00:22:23,963
We have a set of dispositions.

229
00:22:24,044 --> 00:22:25,205
They're your sankara.

230
00:22:25,968 --> 00:22:29,113
With that disposition you enter into every moment.

231
00:22:29,513 --> 00:22:32,859
And a disposition will manifest according to the stimulus.

232
00:22:33,280 --> 00:22:35,525
In this case, ice cream.

233
00:22:35,545 --> 00:22:44,361
So a certain disposition will arise entirely due to the sound of that ice cream bell, ice cream tune.

234
00:22:45,471 --> 00:22:49,256
That can only be done because we have a body and a mind.

235
00:22:49,636 --> 00:22:52,299
It can only be done because we have these six senses.

236
00:22:53,580 --> 00:22:59,827
It can only be done because consciousness with the sense base and this stimulus from outside is making contact.

237
00:23:00,808 --> 00:23:08,458
It can only be done because that contact, the mind, this consciousness, not the mind, excuse me, this consciousness sees their happiness.

238
00:23:09,349 --> 00:23:18,499
it therefore now forms a relationship with this feeling of happiness, which has only as its catalyst the ice cream.

239
00:23:20,862 --> 00:23:33,253
And therefore it wants it, it associates with it, it identifies with it, it demands it, and before you know it, it commits the act, and the ice cream is bought, eaten, and digested.

240
00:23:35,797 --> 00:23:37,538
That's the process.

241
00:23:38,278 --> 00:23:38,799
Now,

242
00:23:41,767 --> 00:23:51,304
Once we've understood that process, we can also see that there is one specific link which is going to undermine that whole process.

243
00:23:52,685 --> 00:23:56,231
And it's right there between vedana and tanha.

244
00:23:57,545 --> 00:24:07,640
Right up until we get to Vedana feeling, it is utterly and totally conditioned by the past, by our dispositions that we have already developed.

245
00:24:07,901 --> 00:24:09,522
There is nothing you can do about that.

246
00:24:10,203 --> 00:24:21,020
Whenever the ice-cream van goes, we will reach to Vedana just like that, which is the pleasant and lovely feelings that arise when we hear an ice-cream van.

247
00:24:21,300 --> 00:24:22,722
There's nothing you can do about that.

248
00:24:22,803 --> 00:24:25,307
That is set by past conditioning.

249
00:24:26,484 --> 00:24:54,990
The next process of wanting it is also set by past conditioning, the desire for it, the craving for it, but by putting our mind right there at that juncture, we stop the next process, which is to identify with that craving, I want, and thereby we stop the empowerment of that craving, and we undermine that conditioning of seeking happiness in ice cream.

250
00:24:57,838 --> 00:25:04,515
Now, in order to do that, we have to be able to distinguish that moment.

251
00:25:04,535 --> 00:25:15,762
And that is the core thing of our meditation if we want to approach the enlightenment through the understanding of dukkha, through the understanding of suffering, which is one of the three characteristics.

252
00:25:18,325 --> 00:25:29,798
When we see that, when we are, as it were, in a position to see that, then we can see that the one is a reaction of the other, the one is dependent on the other.

253
00:25:30,140 --> 00:25:33,784
Dependent, patia, patica samupada, right?

254
00:25:34,244 --> 00:25:36,587
That which arises independent on.

255
00:25:36,988 --> 00:25:48,061
We can see that the feelings arising from the sound of ice cream, etc., etc., etc., is depending on that, there arises the craving for it.

256
00:25:49,527 --> 00:26:00,481
By just keeping that aloofness, and this is what solitude means in its spiritual sense, maintaining that inner aloofness to see the connection between these two things,

257
00:26:01,306 --> 00:26:05,251
And sometimes we're aware of the pleasant feeling, sometimes we're aware of the craving.

258
00:26:05,653 --> 00:26:19,095
Sitting there before your morning porridge, see, not moving, just watching that movement in the mind of the pleasant feeling that has arisen at the very sight of porridge and the craving for it which arises with that pleasantness.

259
00:26:19,816 --> 00:26:23,701
Just to sit there and to wait till this craving passes away.

260
00:26:23,782 --> 00:26:25,145
And there's just the pleasantness.

261
00:26:25,727 --> 00:26:31,298
And then to eat for the purpose of feeding the body, not to feed the greed.

262
00:26:31,317 --> 00:26:33,301
Feeding the need, not the greed.

263
00:26:34,744 --> 00:26:40,556
In doing that, we are undermining all that process of seeking happiness in porridge.

264
00:26:40,576 --> 00:26:43,201
Which is ridiculous, isn't it?

265
00:26:43,221 --> 00:26:44,644
To seek happiness in porridge.

266
00:26:45,721 --> 00:26:52,128
And in so doing we undermine that disposition of seeking happiness in the sensual world.

267
00:26:52,950 --> 00:27:02,782
And in so doing this consciousness is finding a new relationship to the world not based on seeking happiness in it, not based on craving.

268
00:27:04,845 --> 00:27:09,230
To be able to experience pleasure without indulgence

269
00:27:09,903 --> 00:27:22,538
is an important experience in the meditator's life, because then they know it's possible that you can live life without expecting anything from it, without wanting anything from it.

270
00:27:22,557 --> 00:27:23,479
It's a liberation.

271
00:27:24,861 --> 00:27:27,723
The taste of Nibbana is freedom.

272
00:27:29,987 --> 00:27:39,218
In the same way, when it comes to pain and suffering, whenever that pain arises, there arises that not wanting, I don't want,

273
00:27:39,551 --> 00:27:40,675
Yeah, get the Prozac.

274
00:27:42,181 --> 00:27:44,308
Swallow the Prozac, finish your pain, fine.

275
00:27:44,630 --> 00:27:46,676
But the pain is still there somewhere.

276
00:27:47,922 --> 00:27:58,798
In the same way, we see the original pain, whatever it is, emotional or physical, and we see our reaction of wanting to push it away or, if it's too great, wanting to run away.

277
00:27:59,180 --> 00:28:14,182
Just trying to hold that connection, just trying to see it, being aware of one and the other, sometimes being aware of both, seeing the connection, allowing that pain, allowing that reaction to slowly die away and just staying with pain.

278
00:28:14,517 --> 00:28:19,281
To stay with pain as pain is to discover that there's no suffering in it.

279
00:28:20,963 --> 00:28:23,766
The suffering only comes because of our reaction to it.

280
00:28:24,646 --> 00:28:32,234
So, we can say that the whole process of our meditation is to take the suffering out of pain and the indulgence out of pleasure.

281
00:28:33,135 --> 00:28:38,201
Just to do this will make us arrive at nibbana, the end of suffering.

282
00:28:38,561 --> 00:28:43,967
And it is the process of seeing how suffering arises and how it passes away.

283
00:28:52,789 --> 00:28:58,299
When we're calm, then we can also see the other two characteristics.

284
00:28:59,221 --> 00:29:07,778
Easier to see them when we drop down at the point of contact, where there isn't even the idea of it being pleasant and unpleasant.

285
00:29:09,361 --> 00:29:18,556
And that's to see this transiency, this constant transformation, this flow of events, each single and discrete.

286
00:29:19,136 --> 00:29:23,784
No sensation is ever the same as the last one, even though it may feel to be the same.

287
00:29:24,125 --> 00:29:30,255
It isn't the same because a sensation arises and passes away every single moment.

288
00:29:30,234 --> 00:29:37,873
To be aware of sensations, be it if they come from the body or the mind, is to always be in the present moment.

289
00:29:38,073 --> 00:29:40,679
That's why we always center on the breath.

290
00:29:40,700 --> 00:29:42,763
That's why we always center on the body.

291
00:29:43,346 --> 00:29:48,176
Because when we're there with a sensation or a feeling, we know we're in the present moment.

292
00:29:52,375 --> 00:29:58,267
That sense of anatta, not self, remember, is not a philosophical proposition by the Buddha.

293
00:29:58,708 --> 00:30:00,611
It's not a metaphysical proposition.

294
00:30:00,672 --> 00:30:02,255
There is a not-self.

295
00:30:02,675 --> 00:30:04,318
There is a no-self.

296
00:30:05,000 --> 00:30:05,821
He's never said that.

297
00:30:06,383 --> 00:30:07,464
He said,

298
00:30:07,444 --> 00:30:23,125
there is not self everything in this world is anicca dukkha anatta it's transient it will cause some sort of dissatisfaction if we associate with it or identify with it and it is not self not me not mine

299
00:30:23,542 --> 00:30:38,380
So as soon as we get into that meditative posture and we can see, feel, experience a sensation, painful or unpainful, an emotion, painful or pleasant, and we can see it as an object, we are experiencing not-self.

300
00:30:39,941 --> 00:30:50,292
To stay at that point where we see vedana and tanha, the given feeling and our response to it of craving, is the position of not-self.

301
00:30:54,069 --> 00:30:58,615
So, understanding this, you see, it makes our meditation very clear.

302
00:30:59,214 --> 00:31:06,462
As soon as we sit, we must make the effort to come to a point of concentration, at least some stillness in the mind.

303
00:31:07,083 --> 00:31:10,527
And that sometimes takes a little while and sometimes takes a long while.

304
00:31:10,567 --> 00:31:11,268
It doesn't matter.

305
00:31:11,728 --> 00:31:12,709
Just bring a stillness.

306
00:31:13,170 --> 00:31:19,796
And then we access this level of consciousness which is just this observing, just this observation.

307
00:31:21,838 --> 00:31:22,338
You see?

308
00:31:23,617 --> 00:31:26,902
Then we need to have that sort of essential faith.

309
00:31:27,522 --> 00:31:29,944
And an essential faith in our own Buddha nature.

310
00:31:31,007 --> 00:31:33,028
You know they say the Buddhas can only point.

311
00:31:34,069 --> 00:31:35,872
We ourselves have to become enlightened.

312
00:31:36,673 --> 00:31:40,738
So it's an act of faith that is within us.

313
00:31:40,758 --> 00:31:43,181
A higher faculty which will work this stuff out.

314
00:31:44,182 --> 00:31:48,988
Which will make the insight and which will liberate itself.

315
00:31:49,008 --> 00:31:53,472
And it will do it the quicker we get out of the way.

316
00:31:55,057 --> 00:32:07,412
And the quicker we get out of the way, means that when we look at something, we have to draw that consciousness, that attention, into the present moment.

317
00:32:09,434 --> 00:32:16,042
To bring it into the present moment and just to allow the mind, to allow that consciousness to observe.

318
00:32:16,083 --> 00:32:17,605
That's all.

319
00:32:28,317 --> 00:32:31,365
So I hope that's clarified things.

320
00:32:32,308 --> 00:32:34,153
It's not made things worse.

321
00:32:36,961 --> 00:32:42,057
How then, just to finish off the talk, how then would the Buddha mind work?

322
00:32:43,201 --> 00:32:52,053
Now, this has to be in terms of a little conjecture on my part, because it's never said explicitly.

323
00:32:52,713 --> 00:33:03,569
But in the later works of the Abhidhamma, there has to be an explanation as to how an enlightened being works.

324
00:33:03,589 --> 00:33:06,053
How do they actually experience life?

325
00:33:10,926 --> 00:33:16,786
First of all, the avidya, the ignorance, is now vidya.

326
00:33:16,826 --> 00:33:21,662
There's no confusion in the enlightened person's mind as to the way things really are.

327
00:33:22,012 --> 00:33:29,602
So we can say that the enlightened person is now not coming out of a state of ignorance, but coming out of a state of knowing.

328
00:33:30,063 --> 00:33:37,310
This knowing, remember, is not a matter of facts and knowledges, it's a disposition.

329
00:33:37,971 --> 00:33:42,718
It's a way of being in the world which is not going to cause that being any more suffering.

330
00:33:43,558 --> 00:33:47,143
That's what we mean when we talk about somebody being enlightened.

331
00:33:48,270 --> 00:33:55,105
the Arahant, somebody who's enlightened, might need not know how many hairs there are on his head, or her head.

332
00:33:55,625 --> 00:33:57,750
It's not necessary, you see.

333
00:33:57,769 --> 00:33:59,292
Well, what is the Panya?

334
00:33:59,553 --> 00:34:00,655
What is the enlightenment?

335
00:34:00,675 --> 00:34:01,517
What is the wisdom?

336
00:34:01,998 --> 00:34:07,048
It is a relationship with life, which is different from being deluded.

337
00:34:09,132 --> 00:34:09,873
So now...

338
00:34:10,731 --> 00:34:20,134
That person is coming from a state of wisdom, still has the body, a body which can be painful and not painful, and pleasant.

339
00:34:20,518 --> 00:34:21,539
No problem, you see?

340
00:34:22,041 --> 00:34:34,358
But when that body is giving sensations, we're coming all the way up now, straight up to contact, there is no delusion coming from that particular disposition.

341
00:34:34,960 --> 00:34:43,693
So reality, as it were, is not distorted into a delusive idea of the way I want it to be.

342
00:34:43,733 --> 00:34:48,719
And the way I want it to be is to get the world to make me feel happy.

343
00:34:49,510 --> 00:34:54,215
That's your essential position as an unenlightened person.

344
00:34:55,197 --> 00:35:01,724
Coming into the world without any demands upon it, you can see that an enlightened person is very sensual.

345
00:35:02,565 --> 00:35:03,987
Because there's no filtering.

346
00:35:06,630 --> 00:35:09,612
As that comes, pleasant and unpleasant feelings arise.

347
00:35:10,313 --> 00:35:13,637
There's still some sort of reaction to it.

348
00:35:14,278 --> 00:35:17,862
But that reaction is no longer suffering.

349
00:35:18,416 --> 00:35:29,862
there's no reaction to that pleasant and unpleasant feelings in terms of all those things that we associate with suffering, depression, anger, anxiety and all that.

350
00:35:30,972 --> 00:35:44,614
All that, from tanha onwards, which are the sankaras, which are the dispositions, they're the same thing as what we start off with, have now been totally transformed from the vicious to the virtuous.

351
00:35:45,436 --> 00:35:56,574
And the enlightened person lives always in some mode of the four illimitables, either friendliness, love, compassion, joy or peace.

352
00:35:56,554 --> 00:35:57,737
The Buddha himself says it.

353
00:35:58,077 --> 00:36:01,583
When you get to Nibbana, you are contented and with it happy.

354
00:36:06,313 --> 00:36:10,199
Being in that state now, how then does the Buddha act, you see?

355
00:36:10,820 --> 00:36:16,871
Well, they had to coin a new word to express an enlightened person's action.

356
00:36:17,552 --> 00:36:19,677
And the word they came up with was Kriya.

357
00:36:20,652 --> 00:36:49,764
in the Buddha's understanding there are two types of actions kusala and akusala meaning skillful and unskillful what he means by that is those actions taking us to enlightenment and those actions taking us the other way when the Buddha is already enlightened then this business of kusala and akusala no longer apply because he's already there therefore his actions now become and it's translated as functional which is rather dry

358
00:36:50,875 --> 00:36:57,322
But basically, his heart is now motivated to help other people to become enlightened.

359
00:36:58,324 --> 00:37:04,530
So all those actions arising out of a base of wisdom are now for the benefit of others, right?

360
00:37:05,492 --> 00:37:07,054
But there's no attachment to them.

361
00:37:07,614 --> 00:37:10,757
There's no, I am doing this.

362
00:37:10,777 --> 00:37:12,219
See, the grasping is gone.

363
00:37:12,260 --> 00:37:15,262
And yet the action is still there.

364
00:37:15,512 --> 00:37:18,317
The doer has disappeared, there's only the doing.

365
00:37:19,139 --> 00:37:28,693
That's why when this very old man corners him and says, look, give me your teaching now, and the Buddha says, sorry, I'm on my arms now, can you come back later?

366
00:37:29,094 --> 00:37:31,818
He says, look, I'm an old fellow, I could die any moment.

367
00:37:31,838 --> 00:37:33,942
He says, well, okay, I'll give you the teaching in short.

368
00:37:34,521 --> 00:37:36,846
In the hearing, there's only the hearing.

369
00:37:37,248 --> 00:37:38,929
In the seeing, there's only the seeing.

370
00:37:39,311 --> 00:37:41,492
In the cognizing, there's only the cognizing.

371
00:37:42,213 --> 00:37:47,141
So this old man became enlightened in a click of the eye.

372
00:37:47,161 --> 00:37:49,382
It didn't work for me.

373
00:37:54,230 --> 00:37:57,753
So that's how an enlightened person works in the world.

374
00:37:59,152 --> 00:38:02,563
She no longer identifies with what she's doing.

375
00:38:03,105 --> 00:38:09,887
It's just an act coming out of a pure relationship with the world and with people that she finds herself in.

376
00:38:13,833 --> 00:38:38,271
And I would suggest that there are times that even we act like that, even though we might not have cleared the base of ignorance, there are times when through our constant effort to do what is skillful, constant excitement of that motivation of loving kindness, of compassion, just occasionally,

377
00:38:38,251 --> 00:38:42,478
We do something which is done out of an absolute purity of heart.

378
00:38:42,679 --> 00:38:45,644
For the benefit of the other, not for oneself.

379
00:38:55,121 --> 00:38:55,702
I think that's it.

